Let $C=(\Delta_0,\ldots,\Delta_{n-1})$ a clopen partition of $K$ whose every entry $\Delta_i$ is a (nonempty) set of the form $f^{-1}(a)\cap g^{-1}(b)$, where $a\in A$ and $b\in B$. Let $h:K\to C$ be the inclusion map, i.e, $h(x)=\Delta_i$ if and only if $x\in\Delta_i$. This map is a continuous surjection, so, it induces a structure ${\boldsymbol{C}}$ on domain $C$. It is immediate now that both $f$ and $g$ factor through $h$.   
\end{proof}




\subsection{The inverse limit construction}

Given a sequence ${\boldsymbol{A}}_1,{\boldsymbol{A}}_2,\ldots,{\boldsymbol{A}}_i,\ldots$ of finite topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structures together with epimorhisms $\pi_i:{\boldsymbol{A}}_{i+1}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_i$, we can define a new structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ and epimorphisms $\pi^\infty_i:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_i$ through an inverse limit construction. Let

$M$ is a closed subset of the compact space $\prod_{i\in{\mathbb{N}}}A_i$ and it will serve as the domain of ${\boldsymbol{M}}$. We define $\pi^\infty_i$ to be the projection map from $M$ to $A_i$. 

For $r\in{\mathcal{L}}$ of arity say $m$, and $\beta\in M^m$ we let $\beta\in r^{{\boldsymbol{M}}} $ if and only if $\pi^\infty_i\circ\beta\in r^{{\boldsymbol{A}}_i}$ for all $i\in{\mathbb{N}}$. For $R\in{\mathcal{L}}$ of arity say $m$, and $\gamma\in m^M$, notice that there is an $i_0\in{\mathbb{N}}$ such that $\gamma$ factors through $\pi^\infty_{i_0}$. Let  $\alpha\in m^A$ be such that $\gamma=\alpha\circ\pi^\infty_{i_0}$. We let $\gamma\in R^{{\boldsymbol{M}}}$ if and only if $\alpha\in R^{{\boldsymbol{A}}_{i_0}}$, which happens if and only if for every $i>i_0$ we have $(\alpha\circ\pi_{i_0}\circ\ldots\circ\pi_{i-1})\in R^{{\boldsymbol{A}}_{i}}.$ 

This turns ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ into a topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure and every $\pi^\infty_i$ to an epimorphism. We call ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ the \emph{inverse limit} of the \emph{inverse system} $\{({\boldsymbol{A}}_i,\pi_i): i\in{\mathbb{N}}\}$ and we write ${\boldsymbol{M}}=\varprojlim({\boldsymbol{A}}_i,\pi_i).$ 



\section{Projectively {Fra\"iss\'e}{} structures}
In Chapter $7$ of \cite{Hodges}, Hodges reviews the theory of {Fra\"iss\'e}{} limits of direct structures via direct morphisms (embeddings). Following Hodges and \cite{Irwin} we present here the theory of {Fra\"iss\'e}{} limits of topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structures via dual morphisms. To avoid confusion, we should emphasize two things. First, what in \cite{Irwin} is called topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure, here it falls under the name purely direct topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure. Second, in \cite{Irwin} a projective {Fra\"iss\'e}{} class, in contrast with the definition that we will be using here, is not bound  to satisfy the hereditary property ($\mathrm{HP}$).   

We say that a topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ is \emph{projectively {Fra\"iss\'e}{}} or \emph{projectively ultra-homogeneous} if for every two epimorphisms $f_1,f_2$ of ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ on some finite topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure ${\boldsymbol{A}}$ there is an automorphism $g$ of ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ such that $f_1\circ g=f_2$.

For every topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ we denote by $\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})$ the class of all the finite topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structures ${\boldsymbol{A}}$ such that ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ epimorphs on ${\boldsymbol{A}}$. We call a class ${\mathcal{K}}$ of topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structures an \emph{age} if ${\mathcal{K}}=\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})$ for some topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$. It is immediate that if ${\mathcal{K}}$ is an age, then ${\mathcal{K}}$ is not empty, any subclass of ${\mathcal{K}}$ of pairwise non-isomorphic structures is at most countable, and the following two properties hold for ${\mathcal{K}}$.
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Hereditary Property} ($\mathrm{HP}$): if ${\boldsymbol{A}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and ${\boldsymbol{A}}$ epimorphs onto a structure ${\boldsymbol{B}}$, then ${\boldsymbol{B}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$.
\item \emph{Joint Surjecting Property} ($\mathrm{JSP}$): if ${\boldsymbol{A}},{\boldsymbol{B}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ then there is ${\boldsymbol{C}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ that epimorphs onto both ${\boldsymbol{A}}$ and  ${\boldsymbol{B}}$.
\end{itemize}

The converse is also true i.e. if ${\mathcal{K}}$ is a non empty class of finite topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structures such that any subclass of ${\mathcal{K}}$ of pairwise non-isomorphic structures is at most countable and the above two properties hold for ${\mathcal{K}}$ then  ${\mathcal{K}}$ is an age. 

To see this, let ${\boldsymbol{A}}_1,{\boldsymbol{A}}_2,\ldots$ be a list of structures in ${\mathcal{K}}$ that up to isomorphism  exhaust ${\mathcal{K}}$. Using the $\mathrm{JSP}$ we can find a new list ${\boldsymbol{B}}_1,{\boldsymbol{B}}_2,\ldots$ of structures in ${\mathcal{K}}$ such that ${\boldsymbol{B}}_1={\boldsymbol{A}}_1$ and for $i>1$, ${\boldsymbol{B}}_{i+1}$ epimorphs on both ${\boldsymbol{A}}_{i+1}$ and ${\boldsymbol{B}}_{i}$. Let $\pi_i:{\boldsymbol{B}}_{i+1}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}_i$ be such epimorphisms and let ${\boldsymbol{M}}=\varprojlim({\boldsymbol{B}}_i,\pi_i)$. Then ${\mathcal{K}}=\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})$ because by construction ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ epimorphs to every ${\boldsymbol{A}}_i$ and moreover, every epimorphism of ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ to some finite dual topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure ${\boldsymbol{A}}$ factors through an epimorphism from some ${\boldsymbol{B}}_i\in{\mathcal{K}}$ that was used in the inverse system so, by $\mathrm{HP}$ we have that ${\boldsymbol{A}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$. 


Given now that the structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ is projectively ultr-ahomogeneous, it is easy to see that its age ${\mathcal{K}}$ satisfies moreover the following property.
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{Projective Amalgamation Property} ($\mathrm{PAP}$): if ${\boldsymbol{A}},{\boldsymbol{B}},{\boldsymbol{C}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and $f_A:{\boldsymbol{A}}\to{\boldsymbol{C}}$, $f_B:{\boldsymbol{B}}\to{\boldsymbol{C}}$ are epimorphisms, then there is ${\boldsymbol{D}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and epimorphisms $g_A:{\boldsymbol{D}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$, $g_B:{\boldsymbol{D}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$ such that $f_A\circ g_A= f_B\circ g_B$.
\end{itemize}

To check that this is true, notice first that since ${\boldsymbol{A}},{\boldsymbol{B}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$, there are epimorphisms $h_A:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ and $h_B:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$. But then $f_A \circ h_A$ and $f_B \circ h_B$ are both epimorphisms from ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ to ${\boldsymbol{C}}$. So, by projective ultra-homogeneity of ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ there is $\phi\in{\mathrm{Aut}}{}({\boldsymbol{M}})$ such that $f_A \circ h_A\circ\phi=f_B \circ h_B$. Using Lemma \ref{factors through lemma}, we can find ${\boldsymbol{D}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and an epimorphism $h_D:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{D}}$ such that $h_A$ and $h_B\circ\phi^{-1}$ factor through $h_D$. Let $g_A:{\boldsymbol{D}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ and $g_B:{\boldsymbol{D}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$ be the maps that close these diagrams, i.e., $g_A\circ h_D=h_A$ and $g_B\circ h_D=h_B\circ\phi^{-1}$.  The functions $g_A$ and  $g_B$ are the required epimorphisms from ${\boldsymbol{D}}$ to ${\boldsymbol{A}}$ and ${\boldsymbol{B}}$ in respect. 

In Theorem \ref{theorem dual Fraisse} we will see that the converse is also true, i.e., if an age ${\mathcal{K}}$ has $\mathrm{PAP}$ then we can built from it a projective {Fra\"iss\'e}{} structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ with $\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})={\mathcal{K}}$. An age ${\mathcal{K}}$ that satisfies $\mathrm{PAP}$ is called \emph{projective {Fra\"iss\'e}{} class}.


Let ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ be a topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure with $\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})={\mathcal{K}}$. We say that ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ has the \emph{finite extension property} if for every ${\boldsymbol{A}},{\boldsymbol{B}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and $f:{\boldsymbol{B}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$, $g:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ epimorphisms, there is an epimorphism $h:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$ such that $f \circ h=g$. We say that ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ has the \emph{one point extension property} if the above holds when the size of $B$ is one more than the size of $A$. Notice that for any topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$, ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ has the one point extension property if and only if ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ has the finite extension property.

\begin{lm}\label{finite extension to isomorphism lemma}
Let ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ and ${\boldsymbol{N}}$ be two topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure of the same age ${\mathcal{K}}$. Let ${\boldsymbol{A}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and let $f:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ and $g:{\boldsymbol{N}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ be two epimorphisms. If ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ and ${\boldsymbol{N}}$ have the finite extension property then there is an isomorphism $h:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{N}}$ such that $g\circ h= f$. 
\end{lm}
\begin{proof}

We will use a back and forth type of argument. For every $n\in{\mathbb{N}}$ we will construct ${\boldsymbol{A}}_n\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and epimorphisms $f_n:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to {\boldsymbol{A}}_n$, $g_n:{\boldsymbol{N}}\to {\boldsymbol{A}}_n$, and for every $n>0$ we will also construct an epimorphism $\pi_{n-1}:{\boldsymbol{A}}_n\to {\boldsymbol{A}}_{n-1}$.  At the end of the construction ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ and ${\boldsymbol{N}}$ will be proven to be isomorphic to $\varprojlim({\boldsymbol{A}}_n,\pi_n)$. By using these indirect isomorphisms we will get the desired isomorphism $h$.  Let $\{e_n: n\in{\mathbb{N}}\}$ be an enumeration of dual tuples $m^M$ of $M$ for every $m>0$ and let $\{e'_n: n\in{\mathbb{N}}\}$ be an enumeration of dual tuples $m^N$ of $N$ for every $m>0$.

$\mathit{n=0}.$ Let ${\boldsymbol{A}}_0={\boldsymbol{A}}$, $f_0=f$ and  $g_0=g$.

\emph{odd} $\mathit{n>0}$. Using Lemma \ref{factors through lemma} we can find a structure ${\boldsymbol{A}}_n$ and an epimorphism $f_n:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_n$ such that both $f_{n-1}$ and $e_{n-1}$ factor through $f_n$. Let $\pi_{n-1}:{\boldsymbol{A}}_n\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n-1}$ be the epimorphism that closes the one diagram, i.e., $\pi_{n-1}\circ f_{n}=f_{n-1}$. Finally define $g_n:{\boldsymbol{N}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_n$ to be any map such that $\pi_{n-1}\circ g_n=g_{n-1}$. A map like this exists, since ${\boldsymbol{N}}$ satisfies the finite extension property.   

\emph{even} $\mathit{n>0}$. Again, using Lemma \ref{factors through lemma} we can find a structure ${\boldsymbol{A}}_n$ and an epimorphism $g_n:{\boldsymbol{N}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_n$ such that both $g_{n-1}$ and $e'_{n-1}$ factor through $g_n$. Let $\pi_{n-1}:{\boldsymbol{A}}_n\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_{n-1}$ be the epimorphism that closes the one diagram, i.e., $\pi_{n-1}\circ g_{n}=g_{n-1}$. Finally define $f_n:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}_n$ to be any map such that $\pi_{n-1}\circ f_n=f_{n-1}$. A map like this exists, since ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ satisfies the finite extension property.   

Let now ${\boldsymbol{B}}=\varprojlim({\boldsymbol{A}}_n,\pi_n)$. The maps $\mu:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$ with $\mu(x)=(f_0(x),f_1(x),\ldots)$ and $\nu:{\boldsymbol{N}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$ with $\nu(x)=(g_0(x),g_1(x),\ldots)$ are bijections since the families $\{e_n\}$ and $\{e'_n\}$ separate points of $M$ and $N$ in respect. It is moreover easy to see that $\mu$ and $\nu$ are actually isomorphisms. So, the map $h:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{N}}$ with $h=\nu^{-1}\circ\mu$ is also an isomorphism which by construction satisfies the desired property  $g\circ h= f$.
\end{proof}

\begin{lm}\label{1 point=fraisse}
Let ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ be a topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure with $\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})={\mathcal{K}}$ then the following are equivalent:
\begin{enumerate}
\item ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ is projectively ultra-homogeneous;
\item ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ has the finite extension property;
\item ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ has the one point extension property.
\end{enumerate}
\end{lm}
\begin{proof}
It is immediate that (2) and (3) are equivalent. We prove that (1) is also equivalent to (2). 
\item[$(1)\to(2)$] Let ${\boldsymbol{A}},{\boldsymbol{B}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$ and $f:{\boldsymbol{B}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$, $g:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ epimorphisms. Since ${\boldsymbol{B}}\in{\mathcal{K}}=\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})$, there is an epimorphism $j:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$. So, $f\circ j:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ is an epimorphism, and by the projective ultra-homogeneity of ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ there is $\phi\in{\mathrm{Aut}}{}({\boldsymbol{M}})$ with $g\circ\phi=f\circ j$. Let $h=j\circ\phi^{-1}$. Then $h:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{B}}$ is an epimorphism such that $f \circ h=g$. 
\item[$(2)\to(1)$]
Let $f_1,f_2:{\boldsymbol{M}}\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ be epimorphisms for some ${\boldsymbol{A}}\in{\mathcal{K}}$. Then by Lemma \ref{finite extension to isomorphism lemma}, there is $g\in{\mathrm{Aut}}{}({\boldsymbol{M}})$ such that $f_1\circ g=\ f_2$.
\end{proof}

\begin{theorem}\label{theorem dual Fraisse}
For every projective {Fra\"iss\'e}{} class ${\mathcal{K}}$ there is a unique, up to isomorphism, projectively ultra-homogeneous topological ${\mathcal{L}}$-structure ${\boldsymbol{M}}$ such that $\mathrm{Age}({\boldsymbol{M}})={\mathcal{K}}$.
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
First notice that is ${\boldsymbol{M}}_1,{\boldsymbol{M}}_2$ share the same age and are both projectively ultra-homogeneous, by Lemma \ref{1 point=fraisse} they have finite extension property. Let ${\boldsymbol{A}}$ any structure in ${\mathcal{K}}$. Since ${\mathcal{K}}$ is the age of both ${\boldsymbol{M}}_1,{\boldsymbol{M}}_2$, there are epimorphisms $f_1:{\boldsymbol{M}}_1\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$ and $f_2:{\boldsymbol{M}}_2\to{\boldsymbol{A}}$. Lemma \ref{finite extension to isomorphism lemma} gives as then an isomorphism $h$ between ${\boldsymbol{M}}_1$ and ${\boldsymbol{M}}_2$. 
\end{proof}



